# Security Conventions

## Secrets
- NEVER commit `.env.local` or any file with real keys.
- Public keys (Supabase anon, CoinGecko URL) can be in env vars exposed to client.
- Service role keys NEVER touch client code.

## Auth
- Always check `auth.uid()` in RLS policies, never trust frontend.
- Session tokens persisted by Supabase SDK; never store in localStorage manually.
- Logout invalidates the Supabase session (call `supabase.auth.signOut()`).

## Input validation
- All forms use Reactive Forms with explicit validators.
- Server-side: Postgres CHECK constraints enforce data integrity (quantity > 0, fee >= 0, etc.).
- Never inject user input into raw SQL — Supabase client uses parameterized queries by default.

## Error handling
- Generic error messages to user — never expose stack traces or internal errors.
- Detailed errors logged to Sentry server-side only.
- Fail closed: if auth check fails, redirect to login. If DB write fails, rollback optimistic UI.

## RLS policies
- Every user-data table has RLS enabled.
- Default policy is DENY; explicit policies grant access.
- Test policies with anonymous and impersonated users before deploying.

## XSS / CSRF
- Angular escapes templates by default. Never use `[innerHTML]` with user content.
- Supabase auth uses secure HttpOnly cookies — CSRF protected.
- No third-party scripts without SRI hashes.

## Headers
- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, strict CSP — configured at hosting (Vercel).